medieval-warning-ins = General:
        - Remember that every character is a player just like you. Play without causing problems for other participants, and show respect to everyone you meet in the game.
        - A character's life is of great value. The existence of respawn does not mean you can treat eliminating a player from the round lightly.
        - Progress is not saved between rounds. Try to play not for gathering as many valuables as possible, but for interesting interactions with other characters.
        - Try to roleplay a 'personality'; think up your character's traits, story, and quirks. It will make roleplaying much more interesting for both you and others.
        - Don’t always try to “win.” It’s perfectly fine to lose or give in if it makes the situation more engaging.
        - If you’re bored and don’t see opportunities for RP, take initiative—create RP situations, and eventually you'll find like-minded players.
        - Minimize modern slang, spelling, and grammar mistakes in your speech to make your messages pleasant to read. Maintain the low-fantasy atmosphere.

        Rebels:
    - You consider yourselves the rightful rulers and defenders of the island by honor. In your view, the Legion is cowardly and incapable of protecting the island from dark forces. This stance may change during the round’s political gameplay. A truce is possible.
    - The guard must maintain order on their territory. The Rebels have no established laws, but they can be created during the round. Guards may fine and make judgments at their own discretion.
    - Siege is a matter for combatants. During the siege of an enemy city, killing civilians who are not part of the opposing faction is forbidden unless they actively participated in the defense.
    - Don’t destroy peaceful infrastructure. Understand that a wagon driver or merchant is also a player who invested time into building a peaceful, social gameplay experience throughout the round. It’s very uncool to destroy their work.

        Capture:
    - If you decide to capture another player, try to make the role-play experience engaging through various interactions.
    - Nobody wants to sit in a 2×2 cell for half an hour or mindlessly farm resources forever. Respect your prisoners as players.

        P. S. The server is under active development—finding bugs and providing financial support bring the project much closer to a full release.

medieval-warning-ins-mag = General:
    - Remember that every character is a real player just like you. Play without causing issues for others and show respect to everyone you meet in the game.
    - A character’s life is extremely valuable. Having the ability to respawn doesn’t mean it’s alright to casually eliminate someone from the round.
    - Progress does not carry over between rounds. Try to focus less on hoarding valuables and more on creating meaningful interactions with other characters.
    - Role-play a 'personality'. Come up with your character’s traits, background, quirks. That makes RP much richer for you and everyone else.
    - Don’t play only to “win.” It’s fine to surrender or lose if it makes the situation more interesting.
    - If you're bored and don’t see RP opportunities, take initiative—start RP scenarios and you’ll eventually find like-minded players.
    - Minimize modern slang, spelling and grammar mistakes—make your messages a pleasure to read. Maintain a low‑fantasy atmosphere.

    Rebels:
    - You consider yourselves the rightful rulers and defenders of the island by honor. You believe the Legion is cowardly and can’t protect the island from dark forces. This stance may evolve during the round’s political gameplay. A truce is possible.
    - The guard must maintain order on their territory. The Rebels have no formal laws unless established during the round. Guards may fine and adjudicate as they see fit.
    - Siege is a matter for combatants. During the siege of an enemy city, killing non‑combatant civilians is forbidden if they are not actively defending.
    - Don’t destroy peaceful infrastructure. Understand that an innkeeper or merchant is also a player who invested in a peaceful, social gameplay throughout the round. It’s very uncool to destroy their work.

    Magic:
    - Use magic wisely. Casting a fireball in a city just to train, or blinding someone mid‑conversation, is disrespectful, breaks immersion, and may lead to IC or OOC punishment.
    - Progress comes faster in real combat. Hitting a living being—another character or NPC monster—greatly accelerates leveling. There’s no need to cast spells at a wall in a college for hours.

    Capture:
    - If you decide to capture another player, try to make the role-play experience engaging through various interactions.
    - Nobody wants to sit in a 2×2 cell for half an hour or endlessly farm resources. Respect your prisoners as players.

    P. S. The server is under active development—finding bugs and providing financial support bring the project much closer to a full release.

